{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778377860201,"sessionID":"ses_1f07342b8ffes0p547q9RtcnOi","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_sJ2s2x23NLpCwRmpissTEp3P","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: RESEARCH.md\n+# Research Notes: Ferritinophagy\n+\n+## PMID:38714719 \"Structural basis for the intracellular regulation of ferritin degradation.\"\n+\n+This 2024 structural study explicitly defines ferritinophagy as an NCOA4-initiated, ferritin-specific autophagic pathway that releases iron stored in ferritin, and characterizes the NCOA4-FTH1 interface.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:38714719 \"The binding of NCOA4 to the FTH1 subunits of ferritin initiates ferritinophagy-a ferritin-specific autophagic pathway leading to the release of the iron stored inside ferritin.\"\n+\n+## PMID:25327288 \"Selective VPS34 inhibitor blocks autophagy and uncovers a role for NCOA4 in ferritin degradation and iron homeostasis in vivo.\"\n+\n+This study identifies NCOA4 as a ferritin-binding autophagy substrate/receptor that targets ferritin to autolysosomes, providing support for ferritinophagy as selective autophagy of ferritin linked to iron homeostasis.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:25327288 \"NCOA4 directly binds ferritin heavy chain-1 (FTH1) to target the iron-binding ferritin complex with a relative molecular mass of 450,000 to autolysosomes following starvation or iron depletion.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:25327288 \"Taken together, the results of this study provide a new mechanism for selective autophagy of ferritin and reveal a previously unappreciated role for autophagy and NCOA4 in the control of iron homeostasis in vivo.\"\n+\n+## PMID:26436293 \"Ferritinophagy via NCOA4 is required for erythropoiesis and is regulated by iron dependent HERC2-mediated proteolysis.\"\n+\n+This study describes NCOA4 as a selective cargo receptor for autophagic ferritin turnover and shows that ferritin is delivered to lysosomes via autophagosomes.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26436293 \"NCOA4 is a selective cargo receptor for the autophagic turnover of ferritin, a process critical for regulation of intracellular iron bioavailability.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26436293 \"Through analysis of the NCOA4-FTH1 interaction, we demonstrate that direct association via a key surface arginine in FTH1 and a C-terminal element in NCOA4 is required for delivery of ferritin to the lysosome via autophagosomes.\"\n*** Add File: DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+# Design Pattern Notes: Ferritinophagy\n+\n+## Relevant documented patterns\n+\n+No autophagy-specific DOSDP was found in `src/patterns` or `src/design_patterns` for selective macroautophagy processes.\n+\n+## GO precedent consulted\n+\n+Existing selective macroautophagy terms generally use a simple asserted parent under `GO:0016236 ! macroautophagy` and a text definition of the form \"The selective degradation of <cargo> by macroautophagy.\" Examples consulted include:\n+\n+* `GO:0034517 ! ribophagy`: \"The selective degradation of mature ribosomes by macroautophagy.\"\n+* `GO:0061723 ! glycophagy`: \"The selective degradation of glycogen by macroautophagy.\"\n+* `GO:0061724 ! lipophagy`: \"The selective degradation of lipid droplets by macroautophagy.\"\n+* `GO:0061816 ! proteaphagy`: \"The selective degradation of proteasomes by macroautophagy.\"\n+* `GO:0062093 ! lysophagy`: \"The selective autophagy process in which a damaged lysosome is degraded by macroautophagy.\"\n+\n+`GO:0061912 ! obsolete selective autophagy` was also checked; it was obsoleted as an unnecessary grouping term, so no new grouping parent was added.\n+\n+## Applied pattern decision\n+\n+For the new ferritinophagy term, use:\n+\n+* Label: `ferritinophagy`, matching common usage and the issue comment.\n+* Definition: `The selective degradation of ferritin to release iron by macroautophagy.`, matching the standardized definition requested in the issue thread and existing selective degradation wording.\n+* Parent: `is_a: GO:0016236 ! macroautophagy`.\n+* Synonym: `ferritin-specific autophagy` as exact synonym.\n+* No `intersection_of` axiom, because no documented selective macroautophagy cargo pattern was found and existing peer terms mostly do not use logical definitions. Avoiding a CHEBI-based iron axiom also avoids over-specifying the term; iron release is retained in the textual definition with PMID support.\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA RESEARCH.md\nA DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+# Research Notes: Ferritinophagy\n+\n+## PMID:38714719 \"Structural basis for the intracellular regulation of ferritin degradation.\"\n+\n+This 2024 structural study explicitly defines ferritinophagy as an NCOA4-initiated, ferritin-specific autophagic pathway that releases iron stored in ferritin, and characterizes the NCOA4-FTH1 interface.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:38714719 \"The binding of NCOA4 to the FTH1 subunits of ferritin initiates ferritinophagy-a ferritin-specific autophagic pathway leading to the release of the iron stored inside ferritin.\"\n+\n+## PMID:25327288 \"Selective VPS34 inhibitor blocks autophagy and uncovers a role for NCOA4 in ferritin degradation and iron homeostasis in vivo.\"\n+\n+This study identifies NCOA4 as a ferritin-binding autophagy substrate/receptor that targets ferritin to autolysosomes, providing support for ferritinophagy as selective autophagy of ferritin linked to iron homeostasis.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:25327288 \"NCOA4 directly binds ferritin heavy chain-1 (FTH1) to target the iron-binding ferritin complex with a relative molecular mass of 450,000 to autolysosomes following starvation or iron depletion.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:25327288 \"Taken together, the results of this study provide a new mechanism for selective autophagy of ferritin and reveal a previously unappreciated role for autophagy and NCOA4 in the control of iron homeostasis in vivo.\"\n+\n+## PMID:26436293 \"Ferritinophagy via NCOA4 is required for erythropoiesis and is regulated by iron dependent HERC2-mediated proteolysis.\"\n+\n+This study describes NCOA4 as a selective cargo receptor for autophagic ferritin turnover and shows that ferritin is delivered to lysosomes via autophagosomes.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26436293 \"NCOA4 is a selective cargo receptor for the autophagic turnover of ferritin, a process critical for regulation of intracellular iron bioavailability.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26436293 \"Through analysis of the NCOA4-FTH1 interaction, we demonstrate that direct association via a key surface arginine in FTH1 and a C-terminal element in NCOA4 is required for delivery of ferritin to the lysosome via autophagosomes.\"\n\nIndex: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+# Design Pattern Notes: Ferritinophagy\n+\n+## Relevant documented patterns\n+\n+No autophagy-specific DOSDP was found in `src/patterns` or `src/design_patterns` for selective macroautophagy processes.\n+\n+## GO precedent consulted\n+\n+Existing selective macroautophagy terms generally use a simple asserted parent under `GO:0016236 ! macroautophagy` and a text definition of the form \"The selective degradation of <cargo> by macroautophagy.\" Examples consulted include:\n+\n+* `GO:0034517 ! ribophagy`: \"The selective degradation of mature ribosomes by macroautophagy.\"\n+* `GO:0061723 ! glycophagy`: \"The selective degradation of glycogen by macroautophagy.\"\n+* `GO:0061724 ! lipophagy`: \"The selective degradation of lipid droplets by macroautophagy.\"\n+* `GO:0061816 ! proteaphagy`: \"The selective degradation of proteasomes by macroautophagy.\"\n+* `GO:0062093 ! lysophagy`: \"The selective autophagy process in which a damaged lysosome is degraded by macroautophagy.\"\n+\n+`GO:0061912 ! obsolete selective autophagy` was also checked; it was obsoleted as an unnecessary grouping term, so no new grouping parent was added.\n+\n+## Applied pattern decision\n+\n+For the new ferritinophagy term, use:\n+\n+* Label: `ferritinophagy`, matching common usage and the issue comment.\n+* Definition: `The selective degradation of ferritin to release iron by macroautophagy.`, matching the standardized definition requested in the issue thread and existing selective degradation wording.\n+* Parent: `is_a: GO:0016236 ! macroautophagy`.\n+* Synonym: `ferritin-specific autophagy` as exact synonym.\n+* No `intersection_of` axiom, because no documented selective macroautophagy cargo pattern was found and existing peer terms mostly do not use logical definitions. Avoiding a CHEBI-based iron axiom also avoids over-specifying the term; iron release is retained in the textual definition with PMID support.\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md","relativePath":"RESEARCH.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+# Research Notes: Ferritinophagy\n+\n+## PMID:38714719 \"Structural basis for the intracellular regulation of ferritin degradation.\"\n+\n+This 2024 structural study explicitly defines ferritinophagy as an NCOA4-initiated, ferritin-specific autophagic pathway that releases iron stored in ferritin, and characterizes the NCOA4-FTH1 interface.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:38714719 \"The binding of NCOA4 to the FTH1 subunits of ferritin initiates ferritinophagy-a ferritin-specific autophagic pathway leading to the release of the iron stored inside ferritin.\"\n+\n+## PMID:25327288 \"Selective VPS34 inhibitor blocks autophagy and uncovers a role for NCOA4 in ferritin degradation and iron homeostasis in vivo.\"\n+\n+This study identifies NCOA4 as a ferritin-binding autophagy substrate/receptor that targets ferritin to autolysosomes, providing support for ferritinophagy as selective autophagy of ferritin linked to iron homeostasis.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:25327288 \"NCOA4 directly binds ferritin heavy chain-1 (FTH1) to target the iron-binding ferritin complex with a relative molecular mass of 450,000 to autolysosomes following starvation or iron depletion.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:25327288 \"Taken together, the results of this study provide a new mechanism for selective autophagy of ferritin and reveal a previously unappreciated role for autophagy and NCOA4 in the control of iron homeostasis in vivo.\"\n+\n+## PMID:26436293 \"Ferritinophagy via NCOA4 is required for erythropoiesis and is regulated by iron dependent HERC2-mediated proteolysis.\"\n+\n+This study describes NCOA4 as a selective cargo receptor for autophagic ferritin turnover and shows that ferritin is delivered to lysosomes via autophagosomes.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26436293 \"NCOA4 is a selective cargo receptor for the autophagic turnover of ferritin, a process critical for regulation of intracellular iron bioavailability.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26436293 \"Through analysis of the NCOA4-FTH1 interaction, we demonstrate that direct association via a key surface arginine in FTH1 and a C-terminal element in NCOA4 is required for delivery of ferritin to the lysosome via autophagosomes.\"\n","additions":21,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","relativePath":"DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-on